[The 1st case of eastern equine encephalitis in 2021 was in January 2021 in Florida. This is exceptionally early. This was followed by EEE reported in sentinel chickens, and now there is another equine case.

EEE is transmitted by mosquitoes. There is a vaccine for it. The immunity wanes fairly quickly, and in areas such as Florida or other areas where the disease is circulating, vaccination is recommended every 3-4 months. Vaccine is cheap compared to losing your equine friend.

EEE vaccine is usually combined with western equine encephalitis (WEE), West Nile virus (WNV) and tetanus vaccines. This vaccine offers a lot of protection from several mosquito transmitted diseases and includes tetanus. This vaccine will need to be repeated in about 3-4 weeks if your horse has never been vaccinated against these diseases. Then, it may be advantageous to revaccinate the EEE portion approximately every 3-4 months.

Control mosquitoes by using sprays approved for horses to repel flies and mosquitoes. Remove any standing water around your house and/or barn. Places that accumulate water where mosquitoes can breed include things such as catch trays of potted plants, old tires, and stagnant puddles where water may stand; even rainwater barrels left unprotected from mosquitoes can serve as breeding places for mosquitoes. These areas of standing water should be cleared out. - Mod.TG

